Directory services help manage users, computers, and access to network based resources. They provide a way to manage and store user identities, ensuring only authorized users can access specific files, applications, and systems. Organizations use directory services to simplify authentication, enforce security policies, and help streamline access to local and cloud-based resources.

In IT support, different directory services help users log in to computers, access network drives, use cloud applications, and interact with shared resources. The four most common directory services are:
Local Users and Groups
Active Directory
Entra ID
AWS IAM 

Local Users and Groups is a basic directory service available on individual computers, especially in standalone systems not connected to a centralized domain.

Active Directory, shown in the figure, is Microsoft’s centralized directory service used in enterprise environments. It runs on Windows Server and allows centralized management of users, computers, groups, and security policies.

Local Users = one computer
Active Directory = whole network

Entra ID, shown in the figure, is Microsoft’s cloud-based identity and access management (IAM) service. It’s designed for modern cloud applications and integrates seamlessly with Microsoft 365, Azure, and thousands of Software as a Service (SaaS) applications.

Amazon Web Services (AWS) IAM is a cloud-native directory service designed to manage access to AWS resources. Unlike traditional directory services, IAM focuses on permissions for cloud infrastructure, applications, and services within the AWS ecosystem.

Multifactor Authentication
Connecting to directory services requires authentication. Traditionally, this meant entering just a username and password. However, it has become more common to require multifactor authentication (MFA) to improve security. Eg Authenticator, Duo Mobile. 
Multifactor authentication uses a combination of different types of proof to verify a user’s identity. These include a combination of different technologies, such as a password, a smart card, and biometrics, to authenticate a user. Two-factor authentication combines two of these elements, like a password and a smart card. Three-factor authentication combines all three, something a user knows, something they have, and some type of biometric component like a thumb or eye retina scan.

A more secure method of MFA uses authenticator applications. These apps are installed directly on the user’s phone or tablet. Instead of receiving a code through text or email, the app generates a one-time password locally on the device. The app and the server both use the same secret key and the current time to generate matching codes. These codes are usually valid for 30 to 60 seconds and do not travel through a network, making them much harder for an attacker to intercept. Some examples of authenticator apps include:
Microsoft Authenticator
Google Authenticator
Duo Mobile

Shared Drives 
In many workplaces, employees need a way to store and access files together. Instead of keeping documents on their own computers, they often use shared drives. A shared drive is a place where multiple users can store, open, and work on files, either over a local network or through cloud services.

As a support technician, you will need to be able to help users connect to these shared drives, troubleshoot problems when drives do not show up, and make sure the right people have access to the right files. Some shared drives are located on a company’s internal server and use a system called SMB (Server Message Block). Others are in the cloud, like OneDrive, Google Drive, Dropbox, or Amazon S3.

Cloud Drives
Cloud shared drives are online storage spaces that allow users to store, access, and share files from anywhere with an internet connection. They’re used in both personal and professional settings.

Onedrive- Microsoft 
Google drive - google 
Dropbox -file hosting service 
Amazon S3 (Simple Storage Service) is a powerful cloud storage system used mainly in business and development environments. Files are stored in “buckets” and accessed through apps or tools using access keys. It is more technical and is often managed by IT teams or developers.

In Microsoft Active Directory, a Group Policy Object (GPO) is simply a set of rules or settings for computers and users.
These rules can control things like:
-Password requirements
-Desktop background
-Which apps users can open
-Security settings
An IT admin creates these rules and applies them to parts of the network such as:
-Sites
-Domains
-Organizational Units (OUs)
Once applied, all computers or users in that group automatically follow those rules.

Term	Simple Meaning
GPO	A set of rules for users or computers
gpupdate	Check for new rules now
gpupdate /force	Reapply all rules again

Permissions control what actions a user can perform on files, folders, and system resources. These permissions help maintain security, prevent accidental changes, and ensure users can only access and change the data they are authorized to use.

Operating systems support a set of standard permissions for files and folders.

To verify permissions in Windows, follow these steps:
Step 1: Right-click on any file or folder and choose Properties. This will open a window that shows general information about the item.
Step 2: Select the Security tab. Here you will find a list of all users and groups that have access.
Step 3: Select a name from the list. Below that, you will see what the user can do. Options like Read, Write, Modify, or Full Control will be checked or unchecked. In the figure, the Guests user only has permissions to Read & execute, List folder contents, and Read anything in the m1 folder.
